Date: 0/0/1949
Source: Dictionary of Slang Addenda
Author: PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page: 1160
Edition:
Quote: <i>Sandy hooker.</i> A Nelson-born musterer of sheep: Canterbury and Marlborough shepherds' (New Zealand): late C. 19-20. B., 1941. Why?
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1953
Source: Musterer on Molesworth
Author: STRONACH
Vol / Page: 11
Edition:
Quote: The general plan of our muster was this : down each spur went one man, and down each gully another. So we were able to do about five spurs in the day. One of the Nelson chaps - the `Sandy Hookers', as they were called - took the first spur, and we left [12] him there and walked on towards the next. <i>Ibid..</i> 32 `Good. I'll show these Sandy Hookers some speed, ... '
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1968
Source: Remembered Trails
Author: TOMLINSON
Vol / Page: 128
Edition:
Quote: A lot of young fellows from Nelson used to start off mustering there [at Hillensden Station, Marlborough] and they became known as the Nelson College. If anyone said `I'm going back to the college, you knew where he was going. Nelson men in Marlborough and North Canterbury used to be called Sandy Hookers. Stones being rolled down steep faces to frighten sheep were called Nelson Huntaways.
Notes:

